# Java Reflection — What & Why

## What it is

**Reflection** is the ability of a Java program to **inspect and manipulate classes, methods, fields, and constructors at runtime** — even ones it didn't know about at compile time.

```java
Class<?> clazz = Class.forName("com.example.Employee");
Method[] methods = clazz.getDeclaredMethods();
Field field = clazz.getDeclaredField("salary");
field.setAccessible(true);   // even private fields
Object value = field.get(employeeInstance);
```

Normally, Java is **statically typed** — you write `emp.getSalary()` and the compiler locks that in at compile time. Reflection lets you instead say "give me whatever method is named `getSalary`, on whatever object this turns out to be, and call it" — all decided **at runtime**, as a string/lookup rather than compiled code.

## Why it's needed — the real use cases

### 1. Frameworks that don't know your classes in advance
Spring, Hibernate, JUnit, Jackson — none of them can hardcode calls to *your* classes since they're generic libraries. Reflection lets them:
- Scan your classes for annotations (`@Autowired`, `@Entity`, `@Test`)
- Instantiate your classes dynamically
- Call your getters/setters to map data (ORM, JSON serialization)

**This is the #1 real-world reason reflection exists** — it's the mechanism that makes annotation-driven frameworks possible at all.

### 2. Dependency Injection
Spring needs to look at your class, find its constructor/fields, and **inject the right beans** — it can only do this by reflecting on your class structure at runtime, since it has no compile-time knowledge of your code.

### 3. Serialization/Deserialization
Jackson/Gson converting JSON ↔ Java objects need to read/write arbitrary object fields generically — reflection lets one library handle *any* class without needing a hand-written mapper per class.

### 4. Tools: IDEs, debuggers, test runners
An IDE's auto-complete, a debugger's "inspect variables" view, JUnit finding and invoking your `@Test` methods — all reflection-based, since these tools are written before your code exists.

### 5. Accessing private members (with caution)
`setAccessible(true)` lets you bypass access modifiers — used by frameworks/testing tools, but a red flag if used in regular application code (breaks encapsulation).

## The trade-offs (important for interviews)

| Downside | Why |
|---|---|
| **Performance** | Reflective calls are slower than direct calls — no JIT inlining, extra security checks, dynamic dispatch overhead |
| **No compile-time safety** | Typos in method/field names only fail at **runtime**, not compile time |
| **Breaks encapsulation** | `setAccessible(true)` can access private fields — dangerous if misused |
| **Harder to read/maintain** | Code becomes stringly-typed and less discoverable |
| **Security implications** | Reflection can be restricted by `SecurityManager` (though deprecated in Java 17+) or module boundaries (JPMS `opens`/`exports` in Java 9+) |

## One-line interview answer

> "Reflection lets a program inspect and manipulate classes, methods, and fields at runtime instead of compile time. It's essential for frameworks like Spring, Hibernate, and Jackson — which need to work with arbitrary user-defined classes they can't know about in advance — but it comes with a performance cost and loses compile-time safety, so it should be avoided in regular application code."

## Likely follow-ups
- **How would you get all annotations on a class?** → `clazz.getAnnotations()`
- **Difference between `Class.forName()` and `.class`?** → `forName` loads dynamically by string name (can throw `ClassNotFoundException`); `.class` is compile-time literal
- **What is `Proxy`/dynamic proxy?** → Reflection-based mechanism to create runtime implementations of interfaces (used heavily by Spring AOP)
